    <h1 class="text-secondary runner runnertext">Unsupervised Analysis</h1>
    <br />
    <br />


    <p class="w-75 mx-auto text-body-tertiary">
        Welcome! On this page you will find results of our "Unsupervised" data analytics. In traditional machine learning, a model is trained using labeled data, meaning that the data has already been categorized or classified by humans. 
        However, in unsupervised machine learning, the model is given unlabeled data and must find patterns and relationships on its own.
    </p>
    <p class="w-75 mx-auto text-body-tertiary">
        The use of unsupervised machine learning for this project could allow us to uncover hidden insights and patterns in the data
        that may not have been apparent to human analysts. By analyzing large amounts of unlabeled data from mummy exhumations, we hope to gain
        a deeper understanding of this fascinating topic.
    </p>
    <br />
    <br />

    <h3 class="w-75 mx-auto text-secondary runner runnertext fs-4">Clusters 1 & 2</h3>
    <p class="w-75 mx-auto text-body-tertiary">
        K-means clustering was utilized to perform clustering on the data, and the optimal number of clusters was determined by combining various methods like silhouette and
        Calinski Harabasz scores. After analysis, it was determined that the optimal number of clusters is 4. The resulting clusters are depicted in the first two images, 
        where the x, y, and z axes represent 3 features, and the color of each point represents the cluster to which it belongs. The 6 features used in the clustering were 
        selected based on their feature importance scores from an XGBoost classifier that was previously created.
    </p>


    <div class="container my-5">
        <div class="row g-4">
            <div class="col">
                <div class="row g-4">
                    <div class="col">
                        <div class="card">
                            <img src="~/img/cluster_1-crop.png" class="card-img-top" alt="Cluster 1 Image">
                            <div class="card-body card-static-height">
                                <h5 class="card-title text-secondary runner runnertext fs-4">Features</h5>
                                <p class="card-text text-body-tertiary">
                                    Preservation_Well Preserved: This is a categorical variable indicating the state of the mummy when exhumed. 
                                    The options include well preserved, partially preserved, wrapped, skeletal remains, disturbed, or other.
                                </p>
                                <p class="card-text text-body-tertiary">
                                    Length: This variable represents the length of the burial place of the mummy in meters. A value of 0 indicates
                                    that no length was recorded.
                                </p>
                                <p class="card-text text-body-tertiary">
                                    Samplecollected_Unknown: Samples are typically collected at burial sites, including textiles, bones, artifacts,
                                    and other objects. If it is not known whether samples were collected, it is marked as unknown.
                                </p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col">
                        <div class="card">
                            <img src="~/img/clusters_2-crop.png" class="card-img-top" alt="Clusters 2 Image">
                            <div class="card-body card-static-height">
                                <h5 class="card-title text-secondary runner runnertext fs-4">Features</h5>
                                <p class="card-text text-body-tertiary">
                                    Headdirection_W: This feature indicates the direction in which the mummy's head was facing when it was exhumed. 
                                    The options include West, East, or unknown. The variable Headdirection_W specifically indicates whether the mummy's
                                    head was facing West or not.
                                </p>
                                <p class="card-text text-body-tertiary">
                                    Area_SE: This variable indicates the location of the mummy's burial within a 100 square meter plot that was being excavated. 
                                    SE stands for Southeast and is a binary category indicating whether the mummy was found in the Southeast area or not.
                                </p>
                                <p class="card-text text-body-tertiary">
                                    Haircolor_B: This categorical variable marks whether a mummy was found with brown hair or not.
                                </p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <br />
    <h3 class="w-75 mx-auto text-secondary runner runnertext fs-4">PCA Reduction</h3>
    <p class="w-75 mx-auto text-body-tertiary">
        Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is a technique used to reduce the dimensionality of data to maximize variance and facilitate visualization of clusters in 
        scatterplots. In the analysis below, two principal components were created, with the first component plotted on the x-axis and the second component plotted 
        on the y-axis. The colors of the dots on the scatterplot represent the cluster membership of each datapoint. PCA was employed to better visualize the clusters 
        in a two-dimensional graph and identify which features contributed the most to the variance observed between the clusters.
    </p>

    <div class="container my-5 w-50">
        <div class="row g-4">
            <div class="col">
                <div class="card">
                    <img src="~/img/pca_reduction.png" class="card-img-top" alt="PCA Reduction Image">
                    <div class="card-body">
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <br />
    <h3 class="w-75 mx-auto text-secondary runner runnertext fs-4">Clusters 3 & 4</h3>
    <p class="w-75 mx-auto text-body-tertiary">
        The two graphs displayed below illustrate the top 3 features that were used to create each component for the PCA graph shown above. 
        The grouping of mummies into clusters in the PCA plot is based on their physical features, which naturally separate them into distinct groups. 
        These features include bone measurements and burial location, which contribute to the observed clustering patterns.
    </p>

    <div class="container my-5">
        <div class="row g-4">
            <div class="col">
                <div class="row g-4">
                    <div class="col">
                        <div class="card">
                            <img src="~/img/clusters_3-crop.png" class="card-img-top" alt="Clusters 3 Image">
                            <div class="card-body card-static-height2">
                                <h5 class="card-title text-secondary runner runnertext fs-4">Features</h5>
                                <p class="card-text text-body-tertiary">
                                    Humerusheaddiameter: This variable, measured in millimeters, represents the distance across the head of the humerus bone (if found). 
                                    Records with a diameter of 0 indicate cases where the humerus head diameter was not recorded or was not found.
                                </p>
                                <p class="card-text text-body-tertiary">
                                    Squareeastwest: This variable indicates the distance, in meters, of the grave from the east or west of the point of origin. 
                                    The grave is located within a 100 square meter plot that was excavated.
                                </p>
                                <p class="card-text text-body-tertiary">
                                    Squarenorthsouth: This variable indicates the distance, in meters, of the grave from the north or south of the point of origin. 
                                    The number represents the distance of the plot, not the grave, from the point of origin.
                                </p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col">
                        <div class="card">
                            <img src="~/img/clusters_4-crop.png" class="card-img-top" alt="Clusters 4 Image">
                            <div class="card-body card-static-height2">
                                <h5 class="card-title text-secondary runner runnertext fs-4">Features</h5>
                                <p class="card-text text-body-tertiary">
                                    Femurlength: This variable represents the length of the femur, in centimeters, if it was found in the mummy. 
                                    Femur lengths marked as 0 indicate cases where the length was not recorded, or a femur was not found.
                                </p>
                                <p class="card-text text-body-tertiary">
                                    Femurheaddiameter: This variable represents the distance across the head of the femur, in millimeters.
                                    Values marked with 0 indicate cases where the femur head diameter was not recorded or not found.
                                </p>
                                <p class="card-text text-body-tertiary">
                                    Humerusheaddiameter: This variable represents the distance across the head of the humerus bone, in millimeters.
                                    Values marked with 0 indicate cases where the humerus head diameter was not recorded or not found.
                                </p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <br />
    <h3 class="w-75 mx-auto text-secondary runner runnertext fs-4">Depth & Textile PCA Reduction</h3>
    <p class="w-75 mx-auto text-body-tertiary">
        The clustering analysis of burial depth and textile information using principal component analysis revealed 
        distinct clusters based on the presence or absence of data in burials. However, there was also a noticeable 
        separation between yarn count and stitch direction, suggesting that mummies buried with more textiles tended 
        to have higher yarn counts and different stitch directions. Principal Component 2, whose most important features 
        were depth and the presence of bone wrapping, indicated that wrapping and depth were key factors in mummy 
        clustering. Mummies buried with more items are actually buried around 1 meter. The mummies that were also buried 
        with more items were better wrapped. This could be a testament to the importance of who was buried, that they 
        were more meticulously buried, that older graves were robbed, or that burial rituals did change around that time.
    </p>

